It's amazing how these experts change reference points and narratives to suit the situation. Collins said that the vaccines provide a 25 fold reduction in mortality for the vaccinated over the unvaccinated. This fact comes from a CDC report. This sounds like an enormous benefit .... But -

The CDC data set Collins is quoting from actually says that the risk of dying from Covid is - for the vaccinated is 0.054 vs 0.96 for the unvaccinated. That is where the 25 fold reduction comes from.

However, what he left out, is that this is the weekly mortality rate per 100,000 people. In other words, the chances of dying from Covid for the unvaccinated is less than 1 in 100,000 or 0.001%. Importantly, this does NOT take into account the age of those who died or their underlying co-morbidities ... which we know has a huge impact on surviving Covid.

In other words, Collins has done what every salesman and politician does ... he has chosen the number which suits the need for a soundbite and his underlying narrative. Is it any wonder that many of us don't trust these public officials.

BACKGROUND
The coronaviruses (order Nidovirales, family Coronaviri dae, genus Coronavirus) are a diverse group of large, envel oped, positive-stranded RNA viruses that cause respiratory and enteric diseases in humans and other animals. At approxi mately 30,000 nucleotides (nt), their genome is the largest found in any of the RNA viruses. Coronaviruses are spherical, 100-160 nm in diameter with 20-40 nm complex club shaped Surface projections Surrounding the periphery. Coronaviruses share common structural proteins including a spike protein (S), membrane protein (M), envelope protein (E), and, in a Subset of coronaviruses, a hemagglutinin-esterase protein (HE). The S protein, a glycoprotein which protrudes from the virus membrane, is involved in host cell receptor binding and is a target for neutralizing antibodies. The E and M proteins are involved invirionformation and release from the host cell. Coronavirus particles are found within the cisternae of the rough endoplasmic reticulum and in Vesicles of infected host cells where virions are assembled. The coronaviruses (order Nidovirales, family Coronaviri dae, genus Coronavirus) are a diverse group of large, envel oped, positive-stranded RNA viruses that cause respiratory and enteric diseases in humans and other animals. At approxi mately 30,000 nucleotides (nt), their genome is the largest found in any of the RNA viruses. Coronaviruses are spherical, 100-160 nm in diameter with 20-40 nm complex club shaped Surface projections Surrounding the periphery. Coronaviruses share common structural proteins including a spike protein (S), membrane protein (M), envelope protein (E), and, in a Subset of coronaviruses, a hemagglutinin-esterase protein (HE). Coronaviruses are spherical, 100-160 nm in diameter with 20-40 nm complex club shaped Surface projections Surrounding the periphery. Coronaviruses share common structural proteins including a spike protein (S), membrane protein (M), envelope protein (E), and, in a Subset of coronaviruses, a hemagglutinin-esterase protein (HE). The S protein, a glycoprotein which protrudes from the virus membrane, is involved in host cell receptor binding and is a target for neutralizing antibodies. The E and M proteins are involved invirionformation and release from the host cell. Coronavirus particles are found within the cisternae of the rough endoplasmic reticulum and in Vesicles of infected host cells where virions are assembled.
